segments.text: I graduated from there in 1949 and then came down here the following September as a freshman at A&M.
But you did well enough at Waco High School to graduate and get accepted at A&M.
Yes.
I was probably in the second quarter of my class, but I'd been so long number one in my class in everything that I'd done that second quarter was almost a failure the way I'd looked at it.
Yeah.
Did you have favorite subjects?
Did you like the science that you came to?
No, not at all.
The only thing that I liked English, I liked literature.
I didn't like math.
I didn't like science.
I loved history.
The only thing I liked about chemistry was that there was a lady that was a chemistry professor there by the name of Helen Dumont.
I'll never forget her.
I'd been, I was a junior, and I'd been in chemistry all maybe a couple months, and making B's and C's, you know.
One day, and Helen was a very rough talking lady, you know, she was, just barked at everybody, and everybody was scared to death, Helen, do you mind?
And so, one day she said,
Okay, class is dismissed, but Cargill, I want to see you for a minute after class.
Well, that boy, the adrenaline just flooded.
And she said, I've been watching you.
And she said, I want to ask you something.
I said, don't you eat down in the cafeteria every day at noon?
And I said, yeah, I sure do.
And she said, you get a good balanced meal down there, don't you?
I said, yes, ma'am, I sure do.
She says, well, while you're down there in that cafeteria getting a well-balanced meal,
All the other kids that are getting ahead by making friendships and making associations and so forth across the street, hamburger heaven, eating a hamburger.
She said, you're a nice kid.
And she said, I hate for you to see you clam up and stay inside of yourself.
She said, I want you to get over there and start eating hamburgers instead of staying in the cafeteria.
She said, on top of that, elections are coming up for
some of the class officers and different things.
She said, I want you to run for something.
Well, I was literally scared to death, and she knew it.
She was trying to pull me out of my shell.
In a priority complex like you would not believe, I was literally scared in my own shadow because I was in such a strange environment, and she knew it.
So I said, oh, I couldn't do that, you know.
Well, to make a long story short, I did start going over and eating hamburgers.
I did start meeting friends.
And she said, now, I'm serious about you running for something.
You come back and tell me what you want to run for.
Well, at that time, we had yell leaders.
And I never was good at sports.
Didn't play football because mother didn't want me to get my hands hurt because I was going to be a surgeon someday.
You know how that goes.
But anyway, I did play some basketball.
I was a pretty good basketball player and a real good tennis player.
Went to a regional meet a couple of times.
She called me and she said, OK.
He said, what are you going to run for?
And I said, well, I decided I want to run for .
Well, at that time, my dad was a rural mail carrier, as I mentioned.
And he had a lot of mud on his route.
So he drove a four-wheel drive Jeep.
And he had just bought him a brand new bright red fire engine red Jeep.
So on the dry days, he'd carry the mail in his regular car.
And I'd take the Jeep to drive to Waco.
And we plastered campaign signs all over the Jeep.
And I'd run around.
school on my lunch hour blowing the horn and had a bunch of kids riding with me.
And I came within just a few votes of winning the election to become yell leader.
I didn't win, but I came so close it just really gave me a lot of good feeling.
It forced me to get up on the stage and assembly and make some speeches and tell them why I should be the yell leader.
And so it really helped me more than anything I can ever imagine.
And I'll always be grateful to Helen Dumont for making me do that.
That's a real boost in self-confidence.
Sure enough.
And I bought it.
I need it.
Then when I got to A&M, if you ever saw a melting pot, this was one.
My class was the last class to be out at Bryan Air Force Base.
Now, I don't know if you recall that or not, or if you've heard about it.
But we lived in barracks, 20 of us, in one big open bay building.
And we, of course, had an upper bunk and a lower bunk.
A friend of mine who used to live in it, he was my bunk mate.
And his name was Skipper McMillan.
He was my closest boyhood friend.

grown apart I don't even know where Skipper lives now but he flunked out and he kind of always I think felt that you know he didn't make it and I did and so I don't know if that was the wedge that separated us but he had a lot of problems with drinking and two or three wives and he just kind of didn't turn out the way everybody hoped that he would but anyway came here as a freshman spent my freshman year out of Bryan Air Force Base then came to the campus
was over in dorm six as a sophomore.
Loved the Corps, loved everything about the Corps.
We're going to get to that.
OK.
I want to ask you about the time that you were ready to graduate from high school.
Your mom wants you to be a physician.
Did you have aims?
Did you have goals?
Was there something that you wanted?
I wanted to be a doctor, primarily because she wanted me to be, right up until my graduation in high school.
Well, that brings the question, then, why did you come to Texas A&M?
Because almost all of the generals I've talked to wanted to be an engineer, or some of them business.
But almost all of them want to be engineers.
And most people who wanted to be physicians either went to Baylor or to the University of Texas.
I had an uncle, Thomas Elijah Cole.
And Uncle Tommy went to A&M.
He graduated in 1938.
And the whole family thought A&M was just a super place.
And I'm not sure that it ever really dawned on Mother that if you wanted to be a doctor, you did not come to A&M at that time.
And so we just always kind of assumed that someday I was going to come to A&M.
But I think as after I got to Waco High School, and I did so poorly in biology, did so poorly in chemistry, did so poorly in a lot of my other subjects,
that mother realized that probably I would never be a doctor so then she really started pushing the A&M bit.
She didn't have to push very hard because I've always been inclined toward the military.
I think a lot of that stemmed from my intense interest in the Second World War.
Ok, that's another question I wanted to ask.
Why and how did you get interested in the military?
I was a paper boy.
I started carrying the paper when I was 12 years old, which was maybe in 31, 41.
That would be 1943, which was at the height of the war.
And as I would fold papers, I would read the headlines and would read the paper intently.
Of course, during those days, we had no television, but the radio was so real.
And the newscasters would come on, and I'd always listen to the news reports on the war.
Sit in Dad's lap or by him, and we'd all listen to the news reports.
And I developed an intense interest in that, plus the fact that I was always very active in the Boy Scouts.
Dad was a scoutmaster, and I was in a little country town like that.
All the kids in town were in the Boy Scouts.
And we'd go out on camping.
We had uniforms, and I was proud of my uniform.
And I excelled and did well in the Boy Scouts and only became a life scout.
I never made Eagle.
I ran out of time before I
I had to get involved in other things.
But in any event, the wearing of the uniform and keeping my shoes shiny, it just appealed to me.
And so I would say that the thing that really whetted my interest in getting me to A&M were really two things, the Boy Scouts and the affinity for the wearing of the uniform and the Second World War.
The Second World War had a tremendous impact on me.
And how else besides getting you to A&M?
The realization that, well, there was a certain beauty in the teamwork involved.
It fascinated me how millions of people could be involved in a conflict with a common goal.
And that fascination was not limited to just our side.
I had a tremendous respect for the
for the German army, for example, and some of the German generals.
And I'm not sure if I had it at that time or if I've developed it since then and through historical readings and different things.
But the beauty of an organization and men marching in columns, you've probably detected by now I'm very emotional about some things.
And for example,
Stars and Stripes Forever is a song that always chokes me up.
I don't know why, because it conjures up visions of vast armies marching, all with a common goal.
It's just something almost spiritual.
What did you ever consider West Point?
I never really did, and I don't know why.
I really don't know why.
I guess unless I just felt that that was so far beyond reality that it was just too much to hope for.
But once I got to A&M, then the Corps continued to emphasize some of the feelings that I'd already had before I got here.
So one main reason you'd say for coming to A&M was because of the Corps?
Yes.
Because it was here so you could participate in a military organization?
Of course, the Corps and the University were one at that time.
It was mandatory.
Everybody was in the Corps.
So in other words, if you came to A&M, you bought the package deal.
You had no choices.
Either you came to A&M 100% in the Corps, militarily oriented, or you went somewhere else.
But I would say a combination of my uncle's influence, since he was an Aggie,
He had polio when he was a young man, and he was crippled.
But even then, they would let people who were physically disabled in the Corps, they would not give them commissions.
Just like today, we have drill and ceremony excuses.
And I don't know if you noticed or not, but they're the guys that wear the A&M patch on both shoulders.
They don't have an Air Force or an Army patch on their left shoulder.
No, I didn't notice that.
That's interesting.
Those people, if you see an A&M patch on both shoulders, that's what they call a drill and ceremony, or a DNC student.
It means they're just in the Corps because they want to be.
They're not going to be a commissioned officer.
And so he was in that category.
I'm not sure they called it that at that time, but he was in that category.
And I was very fond of my uncle.
He's since deceased.
But that, coupled with the fact that I wanted to be in the military,
I wanted the commission.
Well, the A&M was a logical choice.
Sure.
Now, when you got here, was it the first time you ever came to A&M?
When you got off that train.
Did you get off the train over here at the old station?
No.
Or did your parents drive you down there?
My father drove me down.
And at that time, we came up South College.
Texas Avenue, I'm not even sure existed, because South College was the main connecting highway between Bryan and College Station, and was the main highway at that time.
and it branched off and went to Welborn down on to Houston.
But the first time I saw the college was we were coming to South College, and you could see the administration building, the present systems administration building on the horizon.
And that was the first time I ever saw it when I came down here as a freshman, or to register to become a freshman.
And it was quite a sight.
It was then and is now.
What did you think of the conditions when you got here?
The course of living out, for example, living out at the airport.
Keep in mind that this is a very unusual time for A&M.
That's right.
It really was.
Mine was the last class out there.
Mine was the last class out there.
And out of that class came a lot of people that are still connected with the university in a very heavy way.
Dean Cooper, our registrar, for example, Bill Preston, our state representative, and just on and on.
Lots of people that were in that class.
And we all shared those experiences together.
I really never saw very much of the main campus until I was a sophomore, with one exception.
And that is when they bust us in to go to football games.
And that was terrible, because that's when we really, the upperclassmen had a shot at it from a hazing standpoint.
And hazing then, and I'm not sure, I can't speak authoritatively now, but hazing in that time was intense during the football games.
So we hated football games.
But once we got back out to Bryan Air Force Base, then there was a relatively small amount of it because there were no upperclassmen out there.
Occasionally, some renegades would come out and raise a lot of cane.
There was some of that.
But I remember the freshman year as being a very enjoyable, interesting year.
And we did a lot of things for amusement, football in a muddy field where everybody got muddy and marching to chow.
seeing the movies on weekends.
I mentioned to you earlier, I was a very poor student because I just didn't like to study is my thing.
And I didn't do very much.
Well, I did quite a bit of it.
I've started off as a petroleum engineering major.
Because
That's what the guy in line in front of me decided he was going to take, and that sounded good to me, who was Skipper McMillan, this guy I was mentioning to you.
I said, boy, Skipper, that sounds good to me.
If that's good enough for you, it's good enough for me.
Well, I immediately flunked everything I was taking just about.
And John Paul Abbott, who's still around campus, Dean Abbott, as we call him, he was the head academic, well, he was the head guy with academics on the NX.
And he called me into the office and he told me, he said, it doesn't look like you're ever going to be an engineer.
And I said, yes, sir, I know.
And so he said, well, we need to change your major.
What would you like?
And so at that time, you know, it was engineering or agriculture or maybe something called business administration.
So I said, let me try business administration.
And so then, of course, I went ahead and got my degree in business administration and my master's in marketing and rather my
undergraduate degree was in marketing and my master's degree was in management, organization and management.
And then I took some courses beyond the master's level just to gain some knowledge.
I took some accounting courses primarily.
Never had any intention of pursuing a Ph.D. program.
Now this is a really unusual situation for A&M because you have veterans still on
you still had, I would imagine, a few veterans left from the Second World War who were just about ready to finish up, came back in 45 and 46, and enrolled.
And there are civilians, and some of them were even in the Corps.
And then you also have some teenage Corps kids.
How did everybody get along?
Fine, basically because they had a veteran's outfit.
The veterans were not lined in with the regular undergraduate corps, the younger guys.
They had their own outfit.
They could be civilians, couldn't they, if they wanted to?
If they wanted to.
I mean, they did not have to be in the corps.
That's right.
That's correct.
But all of the... And some of them, of course, are married and have families, too.
Yes, that's right.
But all of the guys in the...
The outfits, that was your family away from home.
And even though you had a mixture of seniors, juniors, sophomores, and then, of course, later on freshmen, you looked out for each other.
And the outfits were very close.
To this day, we have outfit reunions.
And those are my closest friends, the guys that we were in the same outfit together.
And of course, the whole school was relatively small at that time compared to now.
And so you knew a lot of people.
But we had no problems with the older veterans, because they kind of went their own way.
And of course, those that were in the Corps, they would march in their outfit, and they would be in the parades and what have you.
But they weren't intermingled with the rest of the Corps.
I'm always interested in when someone who becomes a vice president and a general, when did they start their leadership?
When did they feel like they were beginning a role of leadership?
When was that for you?
Was it here at A&M, or was it when you ran for Yale leader back in high school?
I think that was, well, I would have to say that when I finished my sophomore year, let's see, no, when I finished elementary school, and I was the valedictorian of my class,
was the first time I'd ever excelled and felt that I was a leader among my peers.
Then my Boy Scout work emphasized that to some degree.
The yell leader instance that I told you about in high school was another thing that added emphasis to the fact that I possibly had some leadership potential.
I would say at A&M,
Near the middle of my sophomore year, I was selected as a corporal.
And there were only about three or four in the whole outfit.
And that gave me some good feels, good vibes.
I'd say in the early days, those were the events that stand out in my mind.
In later years, I belonged to an organization called Toastmasters that did an awful lot for me as far as

self-image, and of course, as you know, being in a job I have here as well as in the military, I have to make a lot of presentations, do a lot of speaking in front of not only large groups of people in some cases, but with very high-ranking people in some places.
And so even though you never completely get rid of the butterflies, you don't want to get rid of all of them.
You just teach them to fly in formations, what else to do.
And so I give Toastmasters credit for an awful lot of my success, if you can say I've had any.
And basically the role of Toastmasters is for people to give different talks.
Yes, right.
It's self-improvement through public speaking.
And it works.
It really works.
So in other words, a role of leadership for you has been a gradual one.
There was never just one.
Some people in World War II told me, well, I just had to stand up and throw that hand grenade at the people.
No, nothing that dramatic in my case.
It's just been an evolving type of thing.
It's just happened.
Which is how it is with most people.
OK, now let's talk about, you mentioned this before.
This is something I am eager to talk about with former students, and that is the hazing.
You said there was plenty of hazing when you came to the football field.
What kind was it?
And I'm particularly interested in the difference between mental and physical hazing.
And also the question, what good did it do?
What purpose did it serve?
Yes, OK.
To begin with, I've seen hazing from two different aspects.
I've seen it as a student while I was a student here.

And then as you get into my resume, you'll see that after I was out of school for a while, after I was off the military, then I came back and my first job at Texas A&M was as what we call a tactical officer, commonly referred to as a bull.
I was a counselor.
I wore my uniform by the virtue of the fact that I was in the reserve, not on active duty, but still I habitually wore the uniform all day every day.
had my office down in the dormitory area.
So I was able to see hazing from the guy's standpoint that was trying to prevent it and to eliminate it, more heavy.
So let me start off with the student aspect of it first.
We had been at the annex in the dormitory, in the barracks, I'd say maybe a week.
We had heard all kinds of horror stories about the hazing and the boarding and the different things.
90% of which weren't true.
We thought they were at the time.
I'll never forget one night about 3 o'clock, about 2.30 in the morning, in the barracks next to us, there was the oldest commotion you've ever heard.
You know, guys yelling and screaming and hollering in wastebaskets being thrown up and down the aisles.
Well, somebody started the rumor in the back of the barracks, and keep in mind that there were 20 of us in this big open bay barracks, that the upper classmen were over next door hazing.
Well, we were literally scared to death.
We weren't about to turn on the light or stick our heads out or anything else.
Well, as it worked out, the upperclassmen weren't anywhere near.
The next morning, some of the freshmen had gone out and gotten a bunch of beer and gotten drunk, and they were coming in raising their own cane.
But anyway, for me to remember that, that made such a tremendous impact on me.
So the point I'm trying to make is the hazing was not anywhere near as bad as the anticipation of it.
The fear of it.
The fear of it, yeah.
But the hazing my freshman year was entirely mental hazing.
By that, there are little rituals that you go through, and they do even today, of introducing yourself in a certain manner.
I'm sure you've probably seen that little routine.
They call it whipping out, where you whip out and stand in detention.
The guy puts you in a brace and sucks in your gut and your chin and all that kind of stuff.
There were a lot of little things that we had to memorize.
For example, you couldn't say, I do not know.
you had to recite the little speech that went along with it, which I can do until this minute after all these years.
But it was basically, I was raised in an environment, and a lot of us were, where the proper conduct was to be gentle to people and to be very considerate of the other person's feelings.
You never raised your voice if there was any other way to do it.

then suddenly you're thrown in an environment where a sophomore with his hat pulled down all over his face gets right up in your face with a cigar which is blowing smoke in your face and just yelling at you and telling you how stupid you are and how insignificant you are.
It takes a lot of adjustment.
But if you know it's coming and you know you've got some peers in the same boat, it develops a certain amount of toughness about you.

allows you after you've been into it for a while to to tune the guy out and say he's not really talking to me you know if he wants to make an ass of himself then that's his problem it's not my problem he's the guy that's got the problem not me we had one guy that and this went on to some extent even when we were sophomores because when we were on the annex our freshman year we didn't
They didn't have that much of a shot at us.
So our second year, the hazing did take the form of boardings.
Now, usually a boarding, I don't know if you've ever seen one of the boards we use or not, but it's a weapon.
It's a weapon.
That's what it is.
And usually...
they didn't get out the board for one guy.
They'd have boarding sessions where they'd get all the sophomores in and give them licks.
Usually the ritual went along the lines that they'd get you in, make sure they had plenty of room to swing the board, move the beds, furniture, what have you.
Then the expression they used was to grab pooch.

That meant that you reached down and grabbed yourself so that you wouldn't get anything injured, pull that up out of the way, and then you'd tighten the muscles in your rear so that it wouldn't hurt you as bad.
And at that time, very few of us had any fat on us.
It was just nearly all muscle.
But when the board would hit, and they'd swing it as hard as they could, just like a baseball, it would bounce almost like it was hitting a piece of,
You'd get three licks at a time.
And they'd be so intense that your rear would just turn red and then sometimes white and then blue and purple.
And it was really a bad situation.
But it wasn't so bad that anyone that I knew ever got injured permanently with it, although I'm sure that there are cases where there have been some permanent injuries.
But then after a while, we got to where we would almost antagonize upperclassmen just to show them that we could take anything they could dish out.
Well, I had a wooden door in my closet, and most of us kept score either on a chair arm or on a wooden door.
Well, every time I'd get my fanny beat, well, I'd go carve a notch on my door.
Well, the notches on my door in room 305 would arm six.
became kind of a badge of honor.
If somebody came and said, how many Nazis you got now?
Boy, and I'd open the door and I'd show them with pride.
I got 12 or 13.
Each one stood for an individual boarding.
That was all my sophomore year.
Never had it hand on me my freshman year nor after my sophomore year.
But it all happened my sophomore year.
And near the end of our sophomore year, the authorities
started clamping down on it and then it pretty well went away.
But that was I didn't really see too much benefit in the physical hazing.
Other than the fact to teach you that you can accept a certain amount of pain without caving in.
And I would think that
maybe in a prisoner of war situation where there's some degree of torture, that that might precondition you to some extent, although I've never been in a situation like that.
But I have been in a situation many times, and recently, where I was under intense emotional pressure.
And I always think back, even, you know, I use it as a crutch, but that's fine, you know, as far as I'm concerned.
I always think back that no matter what those guys say to me or no matter what they can do to me,
They couldn't possibly be as bad as Stanley Rosenthal was when I was a freshman and he was a sophomore, chewing on me.
Nothing they could do to be that bad, and I took that.
So once you accept that the worst that could possibly happen to you is not all that bad, then you go ahead and you almost kind of get tickled a little bit, and you chuckle about the situation.
So in other words, you don't see much purpose for the physical hazing, but you do for the mental hazing.
Yes.
Yes, I do.
It develops gradually.
It develops a mental toughness that you've just got to have to be in some of the situations that I've found myself in and will find myself in in the coming years.
Maybe it performs some of the same duty as the type of hazing you get in any boot camp situation.
Exactly.
It's a mental conditioning to accept adverse situations.
You can't go through life looking for the tranquil way out all the time.
And you try to get things done as nicely and as gently as possible, but you can't always do that.
And so I don't ever mean to be insubordinate.
I mean, I'm a very strong believer in subordination.
It's the only way any system's going to work is through subordination.
But if you get to the point where you can't accept the boss's instructions, then it's time to resign and go somewhere else.
But I've always been very fortunate in that I've always had good bosses and people that I've respected and, for the most part, have agreed wholeheartedly with their programs.
But I will say that the mental hazing was, I have no problems with mental hazing.
I think that it's a positive thing, although it may be hard to see at the time.
I'm all for it.
By the same token, I think that physical hazing serves no useful purpose.
It really doesn't.
And when you came back later as a reserve officer, did you attempt to get rid of this physically?
Yes, and we pretty well had it clamped down.
There were a number of us that were involved in that aspect of the thing, and it was rare, I feel, when we had anyone that did any physical hazing.
But mental hazing, of course, went on all the time.
And with our knowledge, and as long as it didn't get out of hand, we felt that it was a positive thing.
Just like today, they don't try to restrict the kids from yelling at a freshman, but just don't touch him.
That's the thing.
OK.
There's a couple I've heard just from various sources.
These might be rumors, and therefore I wanted just to, since you were on the scene at the time, I want to sort of try to clarify this.
One was I heard that.
The reason why they put people in the airport area, the freshmen in the airport area, was not just because of overcrowding with the veterans coming back, but was because the hazing had got so bad.
Therefore, they wanted to separate the new freshmen from the three other classes.
I don't believe there's anything to that at all.
I honestly don't.
I've never had any indication that that was even a remote
reason for us being there.
And another thing is I've heard from various A&M graduates that they're the most Aggie or the most die-hard Aggies.
The former students were those who graduated in the 50s before this university became
of Coed University and when it was still an A&M college.
What do you think about that?
Now they'd probably say the most conservative Aggies.
I would tend to say that if I had to say yes or no, that I would say yes.
Of course, that, like everything else, is a shade of gray.
But I would say that as far as
what we call Aggie spirit, almost fanatical defense of the university, defense of each other, sticking together.
I've seen it.
I've been here for 23 years on the staff and, of course, as a student before that.
There's a lot of spirit here now, but it's a different kind of spirit.
It's not fanatical.
It's a more reasoned spirit.
It's something that you do because you want to, whereas in our case, when we started out, we had no choice.
But then we got to where we didn't want a choice.
It was almost a type of brainwashing, I'd say.
But it was a welcomed, positive time.
I would say yes, that I would have to agree with your initial statement, that back in those days when it was all core, all mandatory core,

There was a closer group, probably to some extent because it was a smaller group, but we all were pretty well out of the same mold, very conservative, a lot of patriotism, a lot of feeling of pride when the flag went by.
And I'm sure that those feelings still exist, but they're just not as open and as apparent now as they were then.
I will say that I think probably our students now are a lot smarter, have a lot more potential than a lot of our group did because of the fact that they're better rounded people.
We had a pretty narrow upbringing, and we'll never overcome that.
I'm not sure it's a disadvantage, but it's a fact.
And of course, you have to deal with this all the time in your position today.
Oh, yeah.
I'm probably have a broader perspective than most because of the fact that I have been here for so long.
And I deal with a lot of young people.
And seen the change.
Yes.
And I've accepted the change much more readily than someone that, say, graduated from here and then went off somewhere.
But I've had no problems accepting the changes.
I think they've all been positive.
And that, of course, goes right with my initial question that the people who are the most against many of the changes of the 1960s were those graduates in the 50s.
This is the generalization I heard.
Whereas the people who graduated in another very important decade for this university, the 30s, and then who became general officers later on after the Second World War,
Those people have really broadened it in a very different way, and yes, they had the same old spirit, but they didn't have what you said, what the fanaticism of those people of the 50s.
Why do you think there is such a difference in the 30s generation graduates versus the
versus the 50s.

Of course, all being in the same age group, we were all formed by the same pressures, the influence of the Depression, the influence of the Second World War, the influence of a time when family authority was intense most places.
You didn't question parental authority.
That was just a given.
Whereas nowadays, I would suspect that there's more questioning of

And Korea, leading to Korea.

as a result, there's always conflict.
